data.description: Hello Student Veterans Organization (SVO) Members and Friends! We hope you had an amazing summer break, and we're excited to welcome you back for an exciting new academic year. It's time to kick off Fall 2023 with a bang, and what better way to do it than coming together for our first General Meeting! At this meeting, we'll:   Get to Know Each Other: Whether you're a returning member or brand new to the SVO, we're all about making connections and building a supportive community. Let's introduce ourselves and hear your stories!   Upcoming Events: Discover the fantastic events and activities we have planned for this semester, including recreational activities, networking opportunities, workshops, and community service projects.   Executive Updates: Hear from our dedicated Executive Board members about their roles and what they've been working on to make this year a success.   Open Discussion: Have ideas or suggestions? We're all ears! This is your chance to share your thoughts on what you'd like to see from your SVO this year.   We want this to be a space where you feel welcomed and inspired, and where your voice matters. So, whether you're a student veteran or a supporter of veterans' causes, join us on September 26th at 7:00 PM. Let's make this year unforgettable together!
data.name: First SVO General Meeting!

data.description: A workshop series that is created for student leaders advised by CLAC. data.description: AHGSO invites you to a screening of   Portrait of a Lady on Fire (2019) Dir. Céline Sciamma   Wednesday October 18, 2023 // 5:30 PM   Vorhees Hall, 71 Hamilton, New Brunswick Art History Graduate Lounge & via Zoom (registration)   Following the screening, a discussion will be led by Professor Jenevieve DeLosSantos.    Brittany, France, 1760. Marianne, a painter, is commissioned to do the wedding portrait of Héloïse, a young lady who has just left the convent. Héloïse is a reluctant bride to be and Marianne must paint her without her knowing. She observes her by day and secretly paints her at night. Intimacy and attraction grow between the two women as they share Héloïse’s first and last moments of freedom, all whilst Marianne paints the portrait that will end it all.
data.location: Vorhees Basement, Art History Grad Lounge
data.name: Film Screening: Portrait of a Lady on Fire
data.organizationName: Art History Graduate Student Organization (Graduate Organization)

Faculty advisors and program staff will be on hand to discuss the program, academic and professional goals. This unique program combines advanced, STEM-based education with professionally guided business instruction—enabling graduates to step confidently and adeptly into the STEM workforce. The MBS degree provides - externship, internship, executive coaching, an alumni-student mentoring program, professional development, colloquium and more! Please register for this event here.

data.description: Celebrate the end of the academic year by joining Douglass staff, the Voorhees Choir, and fellow students for the annual Sacred Path Ceremony. One of Douglass' oldest traditions, the Sacred Path ceremony recognizes student achievement and fosters Douglass's unique community. Join your fellow Douglass classmates, alumnae, friends, and family as each class is honored with a symbol representing the different class years. After you receive your charm, head to the ceremonial fires on the sacred path to make a wish!  Students should show their pride by wearing their class year colors (first years wear white, sophomores wear pink, juniors wear red, and seniors wear black). Every student will receive a charm, a token representing her class. All Douglass students, family, faculty, and alumnae are welcome! Refreshments will be provided at Ludwig immediately following the ceremony.  *Students in Knowledge & Power will receive 2 points towards their Douglass event requirements*
data.name: Sacred Path 2024
